2 ways listed here to restrict access to K8s API to specific number of IP addresses.

Way #1
1- Allow access to the K8s API port from only specifc IP addresses via firewall rules.
      $ sudo firewall-cmd --zone=k8s-api --add-source=192.168.66.0/24 --permanent   # Create a new zone of the source IP addresses that will be allowed to access K8s API.
      $ sudo firewall-cmd --zone=k8s-api --add-port=6443/tcp --permanent  # To allow K8s cluster managemnt only from it as the K8s-api port 6443 is allowed only from sources in the created zone
      $ sudo firewall-cmd --reload
 
 
 Way #2
 2- Allow access to the K8s API port only via Kubectl proxy while no direct access to K8s API port is allowed via firewall.
    a. Run the below command on the master node.
       $ kubectl proxy --address='192.168.66.195'  --accept-hosts='127.0.0.1,192.168.66.195,192.168.66.0/32'
    b. Add kube config file to the source machine as the below example to allow access to K8s API via the proxy port of 8001 instaed of 6443 and http instead of https as the running proxy accepts http only.
    $ vi ~/.kube/config
apiVersion: v1
clusters:
- cluster:
    certificate-authority-data: 
    server: http://192.168.66.195:8001
  name: kubernetes
contexts:
- context:
    cluster: kubernetes
    user: kubernetes-admin
  name: kubernetes-admin@kubernetes
current-context: kubernetes-admin@kubernetes
kind: Config
preferences: {}
users:
- name: kubernetes-admin
  user:
    client-certificate-data: 
    client-key-data: 

    
    
